My personal experience with this hospital has been a "mixed bag"; both good and poor.
The main complaint is the ER, which has overall good, caring nurses but DREADFUL doctors!
There is a woeful lack of ER beds available, resulting in far too many seriously ill patients having to recline on chairs pushed together, rather than getting a bed...or even a gurney.

However, the main hospital is well run and efficient and-unlike the ER-has caring, conscientious doctors.
I received overall good quality care each time I was admitted for surgical procedures and overnight-or longer-stays.< /Text>

Aahs! has been around forever and is filled with tons of fun gifts. I went here for a Christmas party where we were doing a White Elephant gift exchange.

They had a 90% rack that was filled with Duck Dynasty stuff. I was able to buy $200 worth of  stuff for only $20. It was a huge hit at the party and was a great experience.

Friendly staff and good prices. Check it out if you need something small or random for a friend.</Review>

<user_id>114614326192748927217</user_id><name>Laura Howard<//name><date>1598430529542<//date><rate>4</rate>< Review>
A lovely new place that excels in all areas. You're instantly immersed in a clean, modern ambiance and greeted by ardent hosts. I'm big on simple menus with each dish being exemplary which this restaurant really comes through on. A personal favorite is the Szechuan style chicken with chili sauce, you won't regret it. The Dan Dan Noodle is also quite spectacular with a striking balance between spicy, sweet, and just overall full of flavor.  If you're looking for a lighter dish, the Greenland Halibut is very fresh and incredibly tender. It's not the busiest place as of now, but I can definitely see it growing into a local hotspot. Oh, and best of all are the low prices for the quality you're getting. DEFINITELY RECOMMENDED!< /Review>

<Pics>None</Pics><review>Perfect for satisfying your Chinese food cravings, especially after a night out! Sam Wo is open until very late in the night so it's perfect for those wanting a bite after bar hopping before heading home. The space is a little cramped and very no-nonsense, with some seating downstairs for smaller groups and more seating upstairs for bigger groups. They were able to accommodate several groups of 7 or more upstairs, though there was a 10-15 minute wait and we were pretty squished together. There's also a free photobooth type thing right outside the restaurant that your group can play with while waiting to be seated! Service is very no-frills, fast and efficient. There's only one bathroom downstairs, and there's often a line for it.< /review>< rate>

<Pictures>None<//Pictures><text>Little China Restaurant is committed to giving the Los Angeles area a place to go for affordable and health consciously prepared gourmet Chinese cuisine. With made-to-order service, freshness is assured. A few of the specials include orange chicken, garlic chicken, sweet and sour chicken and shrimp with black bean sauce. Enjoy eating in for lunch or dinner at Little China Restaurant or call for take out or delivery. In addition, party trays are available for gatherings and events.

All the typical Chinese menu items are well represented including plenty of chicken, beef, pork, seafood and vegetable choices on the lunch menu. Vegetarians will enjoy the tofu with garlic sauce or the vegetable chop suey. For something spicy at Little China Restaurant, try the curry chicken or twice cooked pork. Kick anything up by asking for extra heat during preparation.< /text><GmapID>0x80c2be4f8e86892f:0x1e599a6515906f16<//GmapID>< time>

Hoa Slezak< /user_name>
< Time>
1408067708312<//Time>
< rating>
4<//rating>
< review>
Definitely not your average Panda Express, aka crap "Chinese."
This place is pretty darn decent.  The parking situations isn't too bad.  The restaurant is located across the street from Universal City Nissan, in a small plaza, but there are plenty of parking in their lot or metered.  The restaurant itself isn't glamorous, just the basics and not too impressive in size, with daily specials located on a small dry erase board.
I have only went for their lunch specials on the weekdays.  I can recommend the Orange Chicken, Sweet and Sour Chicken, Garlic Chicken, and the Fish Filet in Black Bean Sauce.  Another that I recommend, but does not have a lunch-size, is the Kung Pao Beef or Little China Beef.  Portions are huge and definitely filling.  The egg roll included in the lunch special actually has pieces of chicken inside! Only down-side with the lunch specials are that the soup of the day is only served for dine-in only.  I always have my food to-go. If you order to-go as well, make sure to ask for the dipping sauce for your egg roll (if you need it), a spoon, and hot sauce (if you need it).    Those items are always left out of the bag for some reason.<//review>

<user>108726233374855271212</user>< rate>
5< /rate>
<Text>This location is home to the Los Angeles Cleantech Incubator (or LACI for short). It's a "place where entrepreneurs, engineers, scientists and policymakers can collaborate, promote and support the development of clean technologies and LA‚Äôs green economy".

In essence, it is one big collaboration space with various 'cleantech' startups, community groups, government agencies, and the like all working in close proximity to one another in order to bring about discussion, thoughts, and ideas to the progression of making this world (and LA in particular) a cleaner and greener place.

The LA Dept. of Water & Power has a large chunk of this area dedicated to a "Customer Engagement Center", where customers and the public can come view energy efficient technologies, water saving practices, and the 'home of the future'. People are able to come and view various smart appliances, lighting ideas, and water saving options, all the while learning how to earn rebates on them.

It's definitely worth taking a tour here, or coming to visit, as it gives you a sense of all the new and interesting ideas that are cropping up around green and 'clean' technology.<//Text><name>James Costanzo< /name></record>
</dataset><record>

< review>
This farmers market is slowly growing so this rating may improve over time. Right now the best things are the coffee company that offers coffee at $10/14-oz bag, and the fruit stand with peaches, oranges, nectarines, pulots, and other stone fruits. The fruits are exceptionally sweet and fresh compared to other farmers markets I've tried.< /review>

104499269527308365778<//user_id>
<name>Christopher Russell</name>< time>
1530596365808<//time>
<Rating>5</Rating><text>Great little farmers market open every Saturday. Getting there is very convenient -- a nice walk or bike ride if you live in the area or if you need to drive there is plenty of free adjacent parking. The booths are in the Lincoln High School parking lot on Dana Ave where there are large solar panels which provide shade. I've been getting my weekly supply of fruits and vegetables from this market since it started, very happy with the quality. I also always get some of the great hummus.

It is unfortunate that dogs are not allowed to be in the area where food is being sold, but this is legal requirement for the market to operate in the city and not lose its license to operate. Dogs are welcome outside the food vending area, and there is a dog park at Lincoln High School too. We sometimes bring our dog, and one of us hangs out with the dog under the shade of one of the solar panels while the other shops.<//text>< Pics>

<rate>5< /rate><review>Being able to once again walk to a neighborhood FM each Saturday is fantastic. We get our all of our eggs, strawberries, and stone fruit there each week, along with at least one yummy treat. The cashew-based milkshakes, cold-pressed juice, and Italian baked goods fill that last slot quite nicely.

After years of having a bike she was less than confident about, my wife bought a refurbished cruiser from the non-profit Community Cycles at the FM a few weeks ago. She loves it, so much that I just donated her old bike, and my daughter's outgrown 16" bike, this afternoon. They'll refurbish them, sell them, and the proceeds go to provide bikes and free maintenance to those that can't otherwise afford them.

We'll be back each and every week!</review><Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None< /response>< gmapID>

< text>
What a neat place. My buddy lives in this neighborhood and I was impressed at the way the HOA has used their funds. I dont know if the HOA has any issues but this gives me hope in them. We played pool so that's all I can really comment on and I think the bumpers could use some help. However, we had fun. Also, the space that night was being used by some elementary school kids for a Christmas choir choir event was really sweet to experience even of only from the sound. I did see the pool and hot tub from the billiards room and they look wonderful. We plan on hitting the hot tub soon.< /text>

< Text>
The upstairs area is a very nice place to study. The pools are far too strict though for the most idiotic things. Ive been told multiple times in the past that I was not allowed to use the lap pool due to my age even though I was just swimming laps. If this is a selling point to get you to move to an HOA, then it's not worth it due to the unlikeliness of actually using the facilities on even a weekly basis. There are food trucks every Tuesdays during the summer which is awesome.</Text>

< text>
Years ago, I used to drive all the way from Orange County to Riverside County to get my teeth cleaned by Dr. Michael Simonian. Why? Because, he was literally the ONLY dentist that I could find that wasn't trying to swindle me. As far as I'm concerned, his bedside manner and technique are bar none. He's the guy you refer patients to who might be afraid to go to the dentist. He is super sweet and honest. Sadly, he left California altogether, and set up shop in Nevada for years. I was sure that we had lost him for good. Recently, my mother was looking for a dentist, and she found a certain name that sounded awfully familiar to her. Luckily, I was there when she asked me about him, and now she is a believer as well. I couldn't be happier that Dr. Simonian is back where he belongs, in California! If you are looking for a dentist, please look no further. Because, you will NOT find a better dentist anywhere. This man simply cares about doing it right, and doing it honestly. I can't tell you how many other dentists would try to pull the wool over my eyes, and I would have to go to him to get the honest to goodness truth. Dr. Simonian has saved me a lot of time, grief, and money over the years. Now, he's taking care of another generation of my family. God bless you Dr. Simonian. I hope you never retire or ever leave us again! :)  Yes, my mother and father drive all the way from Orange County to Rancho Cucamonga, just to see Dr. Simonian, because he is absolutely worth it.  If you have Gentle Dental, please make sure that he is your doctor!  You'll be glad you did.< /text>

<Time>1528097985156</Time><Rate>5< /Rate>< review>
Got our food to go. Unfortunately when we arrived back at our complex, the food just fell off the bag and dropped on the dirty floor. Found out that the bag doesn't have enough glue to hold weight of food. Called them up and they couldn't issue a refund over the phone and that it had to be done in person. We were just hungry and wanted our food so they re-order our food and gave us new bag. They were aware of this issue and had a few other incidents, hopefully they'll get this fixed.

Rating is for the delicious dogs and service. The place has an industrial feel and always plenty of parking in the back.< /review>

< Review>
DogHaus was awesome. They have so many options of hot dogs, links and burgers. The quality was excellent and the presentation of the food very nice. The groupon is def worth it, but without a groupon, the prices are still affordable. For vegetarians, they have a veggie dog and sides you could munch on. The portions are good, so you may not need to get a side with your hotdog or burger. Other than that, it was worth the visit, I drove from LA to Northridge. The restaurant felt like a fancy "millenial" wienerschiztel...idk if I spelled that right, but hope you got my drift. You can dine-in or take out. This is one of my fave new spots.<//Review>

<rate>4< /rate><review>As a vegetarian who didn‚Äôt give up meat because I didn‚Äôt like it, I‚Äôm always thrilled to be treated like a ‚Äúfull citizen‚Äù at meat-centric restaurants, and I got that treatment here at The Dog Haus (Northridge, CA location) where they have a veggie hot dog, a veggie sausage, and a veggie burger all available to go on any of their menu items.

It‚Äôs an order at the counter, small-ish establishment with craft beers on top and a family friendly / bar environment.

I was glad I could order anything off the menu and specify the vegetarian protein I wanted in it, though I rolled-my own with the the vegan apple sage sausage with mustard, onions and sauerkraut and cheddar cheese. This was super yummy. The flavor and texture of the veggie sausage was spot-on‚Ä¶the bun was perfect and I would definitely eat this again!

I also had tots on the side‚Ä¶these were perfectly cooked, not over done, not underdone‚Ä¶just the right amount of crispy on the outside with the inside being as tender as it should be.

Pair that with the stout on draft beer and I felt like a full fledged human being eating at a meat restaurant despite my vegetarianism. It was all super-yummy!

My son had a veggie hot dog with ketchup. He didn‚Äôt love it but I think it‚Äôs because there was too much ketchup on it, but in my eyes the veggie dog itself on his sandwich looked pretty good, and large (unlike the small veggie dogs you see in packages in the market.)

Since I was dining in, I wish the beer had come in a real glass, even a reusable plastic stein instead of a throw away plastic cup. I saw someone drinking from a large stein and think if people are dining in they should automatically serve in reusable glasses instead of throw-awayables (or at least ask what you want there...better for the environment and "nices up" the experience a bit to not be drinking out of a plastic cup,  but other than that I loved the meal there. The service was super-friendly and fast and I will definitely be back again!< /review>< Pictures>

<Date>1582788671240</Date>< rating>

<text>WARNING LONG READ! I had a bad experience about a month or so ago. Last night I went back by myself, to the same DogHaus, ordered my food and waited for takeout. I purchased a Groupon voucher the day of my bad experience, and didn't use it. My niece, who's recently paralyzed in L.A. told me she wanted to see me, and to bring something new and different from the valley. I thought to myself she might like the Dog Haus. I ordered the Mensch, spicy chicken, and  cheesy taters. Due,to me using a voucher you must dine in. The young man explain to me the dilemma, but he honored me a one-time courtesy. I didn't have to explain anything to him,  he was extremely generous and courteous. It was late and I was not looking forward to the ride to L.A..  While waiting, I had a chance to watch the young lady at the register, she was very welcoming to all who approached her, and very patient. She also acknowledged other customers as they were walking in to dine. While I was there  the line became very long, but everyone was pleasant. This gave me a sense that they too know that love, and comfort food is being served in this establishment. When my food was delivered to me the gentlemen informed me, that he had given me a 10% discount on my next order. I thought that was nice. I'm  so glad that I'm  a person of second chances. I experienced an easy flow ordering, food cooked to order, and a goody with delivered. All this to say that the drive to LA was not what I  wanted, but my niece eating those cheesy taters w/ ketchup was priceless. She loved them more than she loved the Spicy Chicken. She ate the sandwich and we got to stay up til 4am, talking about the last 2 months of 2020. Thanks Dog Haus, I don't drink beer, but I will be bringing my folks whenever they come to the valley to  visit.</text><Pics>None< /Pics>< resp>

This place wasn't all that great. The atmosphere was more of a college hangout, the food wasn't anything special and it was overpriced. <user>110528804311394807832<//user><user_name>Mark Joslin< /user_name>< date>
1475001334272< /date>
<Rate>4</Rate>< text>
Excellent burgers and sides.  This is NOT your typical fast food.  It's a premium  burger or dog.  Those complaining about "overpriced" need to understand this.

The burgers are generous.  You taste REAL beef, not "breaded" by product.  I've had both the onion rings and tots.  The rings are excellent and the tots are not greasy.  The service has been friendly each time I've gone.  I look forward to returning.  I appreciate the classic rock music and overall atmosphere.  The servers are attentive and the food orders are quick, especially when burgers are made to order.

If you love burgers, Dog  Haus is a must.<//text>

I am post this review to help people with dietary restrictions.

I'm celiac and before I ordered food from them I called the store to make sure my impossible burger would be 100% vegan and gluten-free. I was assured by their chef and manager that I was safe. Minutes after finishing the burger I noticed my usual reaction and started digging around the internet to find out that they don't have gluten-free buns, much less gluten-free and vegan buns.<//review>

<rate>3< /rate><text>I used to really like this place, but the time before last I tried to order my usual and they had changed their plant-based sausage. I hadn't tried the Beyond Sausage before, but I figured I'd give it a go. After ordering and waiting nearly 30 minutes for 2 hot dogs to go, I noticed on my receipt it just said 'bratwurst' so I asked the cashier who rung me up if that was for the Beyond Bratwurst I ordered and he said "yeah, bratwurst" and I asked again "BEYOND bratwurst?" And he looked so confused and just shrugged and said "bratwurst" again. At this point the owner of this location comes over. Let me also add that on their menu, it is literally labelled as "Beyond Bratwurst" if you don't even know the name of something on the menu right behind you, I have no idea how to help you understand. The owner at this point understands what I am saying and begins to make excuses for her employee saying that the menu is new and they haven't gotten used to it. Then she tells me that it'll take another 30 minutes because the vegan meats are kept frozen, but if I want I can just have the regular bratwurst because it's almost done. She says this implying that it is my fault it'll take longer by being vegan when in reality if her employee had just listened to me it would've been finished at that point. I was clearly upset still so she offered to give me a refund. I paid with the mobile app because I forgot my wallet at home and she said there was nothing she could do to refund me since I used the app. I understand that's not her fault, but if she's the owner she should've been able to figure out another way to refund me. She eventually gave me two coupons for free items which didn't really help me because it was only for that location which is the furthest location from me AND it meant I needed to go back there which I didn't plan on doing. So I finally got my vegan bratwurst, ran late to pick up my boyfriend, and then got to try the Beyond sausage for the first time. 2 bites in, I couldn't stomach it and threw it away. So much for all that waiting and my free menu item coupons. I loved the Field Roast they used to have there and while I'm glad they've made a huge step in having an entire Plant Based vegan menu with Impossible Burgers and Sliders and 2 types of Beyond Sausage, it tastes too much like meat for me and it doesn't sit well in my stomach. I literally gave up meat because I didn't like the taste so it's great if you still like the taste, I just don't. I did go back to try it again when the circumstances weren't bad and I used those coupons (about a month later), and this time I did finish the hot dog, but it was more because I was hungry and it didn't make me sick that time even though I still didn't care for the taste. If you like the new vegan Beyond and Impossible, you'll probably like Dog Haus, but this location is now one I won't go to again.<//text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Response>

<Text>Located inside an old IHOP on the Western side of Reseda Blvd.  Very large parking lot located in the rear.  Small entry to the lot from Reseda that's easy to miss driving by. Much easier entry from Baird.  Menu consists of hot dogs, sausages, burgers, and sides.  Handful of beers on tap (pint, liter, or pitcher).  Burgers are well made and flavorful. Buns are King's Hawaiian Rolls (4-per burger), whichs sounds odd but works pretty well.  Utensils are located near the soft-drink machine you pass by on the way in.  Variety of tables and bar seating, with some available outdoors.  Service is decent.  Prices are on the high side, but not ridiculous and generally worth it.<//Text>< Pics>

<rating>4</rating>< review>
I enjoyed the Holy Aioli Burger, which is one of my favorites. My husband enjoyed another fav, the Mench, which has plenty of pastrami on it. We also shared a side of well done tots. We called in the order and it was done within 5 minutes of my arrival. There's a nice bar top that I briefly waited at. If you live in the area, Dog Haus sends frequent coupons...BOGO burgers etc. Also, I received an additional 10% cash back through Yelp ü§ë My only complaint would be the fact that the Reseda street entrance is not accessible for entry/exiting, which is a safety issue given that there's only one other public exit.<//review>
